{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01SSGv2Dx9pyXHToc3Ww2DeS","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior for the weekly engineering status report script.\n\n**Behavior 1**: The content passed to the summary-generation step includes data retrieved from all three sources.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This tests whether the orchestration correctly collects data from all three sources and passes it to the summary step. This is about how multiple modules hand off data — it's at a module boundary.\n- REAL-INFRA: The data sources are external APIs (metrics endpoint, issue tracker API, deployment log). But we're testing that the content is passed correctly, not that the APIs work. We could stub the three sources and verify the aggregated content.\n- MOCK-HIDE: If we mock the three sources, we can verify the orchestration passes their combined output to the summary step. This is testable with mocks.\n\n\n- LLM-DEP: The summary-generation step might be LLM-based, but this behavior is specifically about what content gets passed to it, not what the LLM produces. I can stub the summary step and just verify the input it receives.\n- MULTI-STEP: Not multiple agentic steps.\n\nThis is an Integration test — testing that the orchestration layer correctly aggregates data from three stubs and passes it to the summary step. The failure mode is at the module boundary (data collection → aggregation → summary input).\n\nMinimum level: Integration\n\n**Behavior 2**: When one data source is unavailable, the report is produced with a `data unavailable` note for that section rather than aborting. This is about error handling in the orchestration — when one source fails, the rest continue. I can simulate unavailability with a mock that raises an exception, and I'm verifying the error handling logic across multiple modules. This is Integration-level, testing the orchestration's fault tolerance when a module fails, though it could be Unit if the error handling lives in a single function.\n\nFor the narrative summary behavior, I'm checking whether it accurately represents key values in the input data. This depends on what the LLM actually generates, so a deterministic stub would always pass — this makes it Agentic. The minimum level here is Agentic.\n\nNow looking at the complete end-to-end report delivery: this chains data collection from multiple sources through LLM summary generation to email delivery. It requires real email infrastructure to verify the message actually reaches the recipient's inbox, and the email content itself depends on what the LLM generates. This is clearly a System-level test because it spans the entire pipeline with real infrastructure dependencies and LLM variability. This is a full agent pipeline, so Workflow fits. The key question is whether correctness hinges on the LLM output — and it does, since \"reaches the inbox correctly\" means the content matters, not just delivery. With real external APIs, real LLM generation, and real email delivery involved, this lands at least at System level, probably Workflow.\n\nFor the fallback behavior, I'm looking at error handling when email delivery fails — the system saves the report locally and retries on the next scheduled run. That's testing the resilience layer plus the filesystem interaction.\n\nThe tricky part is the retry piece: testing that it actually retries on the next run requires either running the scheduler again (System-level) or invoking the retry logic directly (Integration-level). The file-writing part is straightforward Integration, but the full behavior spans multiple executions.\n\nI think Integration is sufficient here—I can stub the email service, use a real or in-process filesystem, and call the function twice in sequence to simulate the retry without needing actual subprocess invocation.\n\nSo my final test levels are: Integration for multi-source data aggregation, Integration for graceful degradation when a source fails, Agentic for LLM summary quality, Workflow for the end-to-end pipeline, and Integration for the email failure fallback with file persistence and retry logic.\n\nNow I'm assigning confidence levels to each behavior based on what test level is most appropriate. For the multi-source data passing, Integration is most likely at 70% since it crosses module boundaries. Graceful degradation also lands at Integration with 70% probability since error handling spans the pipeline. The narrative accuracy behavior is primarily Agentic, though Integration could play a minor role.\n\nThe complete pipeline to inbox is almost certainly a Workflow test at 75%, since it exercises the entire system end-to-end. Email failure with retry logic is split between Integration at 55% and System at 30%, accounting for whether the retry mechanism needs subprocess-level handling.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9657,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9657},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ce4d2ef1-cf76-4b2c-82dd-0de17676c438","uuid":"13f37540-0986-4465-81bb-e85cc894267d"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01SSGv2Dx9pyXHToc3Ww2DeS","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_012g2xxdk79pqVxHrQNWna5G","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The content passed to the summary-generation step includes data retrieved from all three sources.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is at the boundary between data collection and the aggregation/routing layer — if any one source's data is dropped or miskeyed before being forwarded, a unit test on a single function won't catch it. The bug only appears when the three collection modules and the orchestrator are wired together. REAL-INFRA: The three sources are external APIs, but for this behavior we care only that their (stubbable) responses reach the summary step — no real network needed. MOCK-HIDE: Stubbing all three sources with deterministic responses and asserting the summary-step receives all three payloads is exactly the right approach; nothing is hidden. LLM-DEP: We are asserting on the *input* to the summary step, not its output, so the LLM itself need not run. MULTI-STEP: No chained agentic steps. REJECTION-GATE: System was rejected because stubbed HTTP clients fully reproduce the failure. Agentic was rejected because we never depend on what the model produces.","test_description":"Stub all three data sources (metrics endpoint, issue tracker API, deployment log) with distinct deterministic payloads. Stub the summary-generation step to capture its input. Invoke the data-collection orchestrator and assert that the captured input contains identifiable markers from each of the three stub responses.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When one data source is unavailable, the report is produced with a `data unavailable` note for that section rather than aborting.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode spans two module boundaries: the collection layer must catch the exception from one source and inject a sentinel value, and the orchestrator must continue and pass a partial payload to the report-assembly layer. A unit test on the fallback function alone misses whether the sentinel propagates correctly. REAL-INFRA: Unavailability is simulated by making one stub raise a connection error; no real network is needed. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the failing source is appropriate here since we want to test the error-handling path, not the API itself. LLM-DEP: None — we are asserting on report structure, not summary quality. MULTI-STEP: No chained agentic steps. REJECTION-GATE: System rejected because an in-process stub that raises an exception faithfully reproduces the failure without real infrastructure.","test_description":"Stub two sources with valid responses and configure the third stub to raise a connection error. Run the full collection-and-report-assembly pipeline. Assert the resulting report object contains valid data for the two healthy sections and a `data unavailable` string in the section corresponding to the failing source, and that no exception propagates to the caller.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The narrative summary accurately represents the key values present in the input data.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: The script 'generates a narrative summary' — the accuracy of that summary is the assertion under test. A deterministic stub that returns a fixed string always passes regardless of whether the real model correctly captures key values, omits figures, or hallucinates numbers. The only way to catch a failure is to run the real model. MOCK-HIDE: Replacing the LLM with a fixed response completely hides the failure mode described. REAL-INFRA: No OS/subprocess dependency beyond the API call itself. MULTI-STEP: Single LLM call, so Workflow is not required. REJECTION-GATE: Integration was rejected because the correctness criterion ('accurately represents key values') is a judgment about model output quality, not about infrastructure routing. Unit was rejected for the same reason.","test_description":"Supply a structured input payload containing several specific numeric values and named entities (e.g., deployment count, P95 latency, open critical bugs). Call the real summary-generation API with this payload. Assert that the returned narrative text contains or accurately paraphrases each key value. Run multiple times and treat consistent omissions or distortions as a failure.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.8,"Workflow":0.07}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A complete report — from data collection through email delivery — reaches the configured recipient's inbox correctly.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"MULTI-STEP: The pipeline sequences: (1) three real or semi-real data-source calls, (2) a real LLM summary-generation call whose output determines report content, (3) real email delivery to a real inbox. This matches 'multiple agentic steps in sequence, or a full agent pipeline.' REAL-INFRA: 'reaches the configured recipient's inbox' requires real email delivery (or at minimum a real SMTP sink that accepts and stores messages); an in-process fake that accepts calls without actually delivering cannot verify inbox receipt. LLM-DEP: The report content depends on LLM output; a stub replaces the model's judgment with a constant, hiding any generation failure. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking both the LLM and the email transport makes it impossible to verify that (a) the generated content is coherent and (b) actual delivery succeeded. REJECTION-GATE: Agentic was considered but rejected upward because the test also requires real email delivery infrastructure, and the pipeline has multiple sequenced stages (data → LLM → SMTP). System alone was rejected because model output quality is also under test.","test_description":"Configure the script against a real (sandboxed) SMTP server or mailbox (e.g., a local Mailpit instance or a dedicated test inbox). Point data sources at real or staging endpoints. Execute the full script. After completion, poll the test inbox and assert a message arrived addressed to the configured recipient, that the subject line matches the expected format, and that the body contains meaningful content derived from the collected data.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.11,"Agentic":0.15,"Workflow":0.7}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the email delivery service is unreachable, the generated report is saved to a local file and delivery is retried on the next scheduled run.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The behavior spans two module interactions: the delivery layer must catch the SMTP failure and hand off to the file-persistence layer, and on a subsequent invocation the orchestrator must detect the saved file and re-attempt delivery. This crosses at least two module boundaries. REAL-INFRA: The SMTP failure is reproduced by a stub that raises a connection error; no real mail server is needed. The file write and subsequent re-read exercise the real local filesystem, but that is not a System-level concern — in-process filesystem I/O is Integration-appropriate. The 'next scheduled run' is reproduced by invoking the same entry-point function a second time in the same test process. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking SMTP to raise is correct here; we want to test the fallback path. LLM-DEP: The report content can be a pre-generated stub since we are testing the delivery and retry path, not summary quality. MULTI-STEP: No chained agentic steps. REJECTION-GATE: System was considered because 'next scheduled run' implies subprocess re-invocation, but the behavior's own failure mode (state not persisted, retry not triggered) is fully reproducible by calling the entry point twice within one test process using a real temp directory. Workflow rejected: no LLM steps are required to test this path.","test_description":"Configure the SMTP client stub to raise a connection error on every call. Provide a pre-generated report object. Invoke the delivery function and assert it writes the report to a designated local file path. Then re-invoke the full delivery entry-point (simulating the next scheduled run) with the SMTP stub now succeeding. Assert that (a) the file is consumed/deleted and (b) the SMTP stub received the report content from the saved file.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.58,"System":0.28,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.03}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9657,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9657},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ce4d2ef1-cf76-4b2c-82dd-0de17676c438","uuid":"9c8a595b-5a7b-4545-957a-8cb2426cc413"}
